How to Solve 3A

Here you will analyze three alternative policies for reducing water use among these irrigation districts.In total, these irrigation districts will need to reduce water consumption from the current 755 AF down to 500 AF. For each intervention listed below, perform the following calculations: (1) calculate the stringency of the policy (defined below for each intervention) required to achieve the 500 AF target, (2) calculate the total cost of meeting the target using that approach, (3) calculate the cost to each district, and (4) calculate the tax revenue generated.

  1. Cap without trade. Reduce each district’s water use by the same fraction (e.g., 1/3 of current baseline use), so the 500 AF target is met. Trade is not allowed. Stringency is defined as the magnitude of the fraction.
  • Using the baseline in each of the four cities, I set up an equation where the same fraction for each city times each city’s baseline sums to 225. (225 is the amount of abatement that is needed (755-500))
  • p150 + p145 + p220 + p245 = 255
  • p = 0.338
  • Each city will reduce their water usage by 0.338 to achieve the policy [0.338 stringency]
  • No tax revenue generated

Kern county: Abatement = baseline x 0.338 Abatement = 150 X 0.338 Abatement = 50.7

Mojave County: Abatement = baseline x 0.338 Abatement = 140 X 0.338 Abatement = 47.32

Antelope County: Abatement = baseline x 0.338 Abatement = 220 X 0.338 Abatement = 74.36

Ventura County: Abatement = baseline x 0.338 Abatement = 245 X 0.338 Abatement = 82.81

  1. Tax on water use. A single tax is implemented on all water use in each of the four districts, such that water use is reduced to the 500 AF target. Stringency is defined as the magnitude of the tax.

To calculate the tax, I first need to find the Aggregated Marginal Cost equation. - This is done by first converting all of my marginal cost equations to solve for the Q variable because I will be horizontally summing and the Q value is the X value.

Kern County : P=2.286Q - Q(kern) = (1/2.286)P

Mojave County: P=3.804Q - Q(mojave) = (1/3.804)P

Antelope County: P=2.858Q - Q(antelope) = (1/2.858)P

Ventura County: P=1.776Q - Q(ventura) = (1/1.776)P

Q(agg) = Q(kern) + Q(mojave) + Q(antelope) + Q(ventura) Q(agg) = (1/2.286)P + (1/3.804)P + (1/2.858)P + (1/1.776)P Q(agg) = 1.613(P)

Now, to find P* at the Q* value, I plug in 255 as Qagg, because this is the amount of abatement that we want and then solve for P

255 = 1.613(P) P = 158.09 P* = 158.09

Now, we need to calculate the Q value (quantity abated) associated with this P for each district/county’s marginal demand curve. To do this, we plug in P = 158.062 into each of the marginal cost curves.

Kern County : - Q(kern) = (1/2.286)(158.09) - Q(kern) = 69.14

Mojave County: P=3.804Q - Q(mojave) = (1/3.804)(158.09) - Q(mojave) = 41.56

Antelope County: P=2.858Q - Q(antelope) = (1/2.858)(158.09) - Q(antelope) = 55.31

Ventura County: P=1.776Q - Q(ventura) = (1/1.776)(158.09) - Q(ventura) = 89.01

  1. Cap and trade. Cap water use as in part (a), but after those caps are set, allow trade across districts. How much water is used by each district after trade? Stringency is the same as in part (a).

However because trading is allowed, the districts will buy and sell their water rights, to reach the socially optimal point which is what we found under part b. Therefore in the end, Kern abates 69.14 AF, Mojave abates 41.56 AF, Antelope abates 55.31 AF, and Ventura abates 89.01 AF.
